Data Wrangling

# remove the NAs
d1980 <- na.omit(d1980)
d1990 <- na.omit(d1990)
d2000 <- na.omit(d2000)
d2010 <- na.omit(d2010)
# removed bracketed values from each year
d1980 <- d1980 %>% 
  mutate(`Year[I]` = trimws(str_replace(`Year[I]`, "\\[.*?\\]", "")))
d1990 <- d1990 %>% 
  mutate(`Year[I]` = trimws(str_replace(`Year[I]`, "\\[.*?\\]", "")))
d2000 <- d2000 %>% 
  mutate(`Year[I]` = trimws(str_replace(`Year[I]`, "\\[.*?\\]", "")))
d2010 <- d2010 %>% 
  mutate(`Year[I]` = trimws(str_replace(`Year[I]`, "\\[.*?\\]", "")))
# clean variables
d1980 <- d1980 %>% 
  rename(year = `Year[I]`,
         track = Record,
         artist = `Artist(s)`) %>%
  subset(select = -c(`Production team`))

d1990 <- d1990 %>% 
  rename(year = `Year[I]`,
         track = Record,
         artist = `Artist(s)`) %>%
  subset(select = -c(`Production team`))

d2000 <- d2000 %>% 
  rename(year = `Year[I]`,
         track = Record,
         artist = `Artist(s)`) %>%
  subset(select = -c(`Production team`))

d2010 <- d2010 %>% 
  rename(year = `Year[I]`,
         track = Record,
         artist = `Artist(s)`) %>%
  subset(select = -c(`Production team`))
# make a table with lyrics for each song in 1980s
lyrics80s <- d1980 %>%
  add_genius(artist, track, type = "lyrics")
# make a table with lyrics for each song in 1990s
lyrics90s <- d1990 %>%
  add_genius(artist, track, type = "lyrics")
# make a table with lyrics for each song in 2000s
lyrics00s <- d2000 %>%
  add_genius(artist, track, type = "lyrics")
# make a table with lyrics for each song in 2010s
lyrics10s <- d2010 %>%
  add_genius(artist, track, type = "lyrics")
# join all lyrics data frames
allLyrics <- rbind(lyrics80s, lyrics90s, lyrics00s, lyrics10s)
# add decades variable
allLyrics <- allLyrics %>%
mutate(decade = ifelse(year %in% 1980:1989, "1980s",
                                     ifelse(year %in% 1990:1999, "1990s",
                                            ifelse(year %in% 2000:2009, "2000s",
                                                   ifelse(year %in% 2010:2019, "2010s", "NA")))))

Data Visualization

Graph 1

# create data frame to extract words in each song into new variable "word"
wordsPerSong1 <-
  allLyrics %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, lyric) %>%
  select(decade, track_title, word)

# find count of words per track
wordsPerSong2 <-
  aggregate(word ~ track_title, data = wordsPerSong, NROW)

# create new data frame joining two frames
wordsPerSong <-
  left_join(wordsPerSong1, wordsPerSong2, by="track_title") %>%
  subset(select = -c(`word.x`)) %>%
  rename(avgWord = word.y) %>%
  group_by(track_title) %>%
  distinct(track_title, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  na.omit()
# create graph 1 using wordsPerSong data frame
ggplot(wordsPerSong) +
 aes(x = decade, y = avg_word, fill = decade) +
 geom_boxplot() +
 labs(x = "Decade", y = "Words per Song", title = "Boxplots of Words per Grammy Nominated Song by Decade") +
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="BuPu")

Graph 1 is showing the distribution of song word count for each decade. This graph also includes stop words, so the word count includes simple terms like “the”, “a”, and others. The boxplots show that the 2000s had the largest spread of word count in songs, and the high outlier of almost 1000 words appears to be the highest word count for a single song.

Graph 2

# remove stop words
word = data.frame()
word[1,1]=c('ba')
word[2,1]=c('du')
word[3,1]=c('yeah')
word[4,1]=c('da')
word[5,1]=c('ya')
word[6,1]=c('ooh')
word[7,1]=c('gonna')
word[8,1]=c('na')
word[9,1]=c('uh')
word[10,1]=c('la')
word[11,1]=c('hol')
colnames(word) <- c('word')

verse_words <- allLyrics %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, lyric)

ft <- verse_words %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  anti_join(word)

In order to remove the 11 addition stop words from the data, I created a single column data frame called “word” which included all of the specified values. I used the function unnest_tokens to extract the words from each line of the lyrics data frame. Then finally, using anti_join, I removed the stop_words from the tidytext package as well as the 11 stop words from the data frame “word”.

# create data frame of top 10 words
topten <- ft %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10)
# create graph of top 10 words
ggplot(topten) +
 aes(x = reorder(word, -n), fill = word, weight = n) +
 geom_bar(fill = "#f8b195") +
 labs(x = "Word", y = "Count", title = "Ten Most Popular Words of Grammy Nominated Songs from 1980 - 2019") +
 theme_linedraw() +
 theme(legend.position = "none")

Graph 2 is showing the ten most popular words of all Grammy nominated songs from 1980 to 2019. The bar graph allows the count of each word to be compared across the top 10 words. The graph shows that “love” was the most popular word by a significant amount, since it leads by over 300.

graph80s <- ft %>%
  filter(decade == "1980s") %>%
  select(decade, track_title, word) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10)

# create data frame for top ten for 1990s

  top_n(10)

# create data frame for top ten for 2000s
graph00s <- ft %>%
  filter(decade == "2000s") %>%
